The web interface is deployed using a @Docker swarm stack on @mrcclimb and uses a simple pure-JS frontend with Python on the backend, implemented with @tiangolo‚Äôs superb FastAPI. We use Celery+@RabbitMQ+Redis for task management.

The program no longer fails if no primers can be found, opening up gaps if necessary. Jobs are fast to run and provide real time progress indicators to the user. If particular references cause repeated alignment failures (e.g. too diverse) they are automatically dropped.

We implemented an algorithm to avoid primer-primer interactions using Primer3 thermodynamic simulations to predict 3' interactions between primers in the same pool. This avoids unwanted dimer formation as observed by @ItoKenta in the @articnetwork nCoV-2019 scheme.

Primers are scored by blending the base penalty with a mismatch score calculated from the alignments to all other genomes. 3' mismatches are more heavily penalised to fit with our observations from work with @NathanGrubaugh @K_G_Andersen https://t.co/9ByugzezpQ.

Primers are now designed against all input sequences; we did this by reimplementing the Primer3 design primers routine so we could make it work how we needed. The old behaviour of only considering primary reference primers can be restored using the --pinned option.

v1.2.1 has many improvements to the algorithm and is now available from PyPI, making it much easier to install via pip on Mac, Linux and Windows. Using https://t.co/xTIzfFQ01L to perform fast glocal alignments allowed us to drop our dependency on subpackages to enable this.

primalscheme is a tool for designing primers for multiplex PCR which we developed for real-time surveillance of Zika virus but had been been widely used by @CovidGenomicsUK sites in generating almost 30,000 genomes.

It was nice that our approach for 3D nuclear shape analysis (https://t.co/iS1bIb3ylX) worked well to quantify changes in VPA-treated astrocytes, reflecting chromatin re-organization. Curious to look deeper into this in the context of astrocyte-to-neuron reprogramming.[6/6]

Indeed, we found that VPA-treatment induced much more globally irregular nuclear shapes (kidney-like or with "blebs") with many local irregularities as well, like "bumps" and concavities.[5/6] https://t.co/89jgH7bwgu

We found increase in size of both normal and VPA-treated astrocyte nuclei, but by day 7 VPA treatment led to 13% elongation in major axis length, 23% increase in nuclear volume, and 40% increase in bounding primitive volume (which tells us something about shape!).[4/6] https://t.co/iEMzlCfpAW

To quantify VPA-induced changes in 3D nuclear morphology, we compared voxel and surface-modeled representations of nuclear form andidentified 11 representative surface-based size and shape features, which gave us 85% AUC on day 7 vs untreated cells.[3/6] https://t.co/pIuwNTu18Y

Valproic acid (VPA) is an HDAC inhibitor that has potential for astrocyte-to-neuron cell reprogramming & implications for cell replacement therapy of TBI, ischemia, etc. VPA induces chromatin decondensation, but how that affects 3D nuclear morphology is not well studied.[2/6]

Excited to share our new paper:Valproic Acid-Induced Changes of 4D Nuclear Morphology in Astrocyte Cells We used shape modeling to quantify temporal dynamics of 3D nuclear morphology in VPA-treated human astrocytes in 7-day imaging study.Link: https://t.co/jKaKnnTqI7[1/6] https://t.co/E8POnFp36f

To finish on a lighter note, given how little we still know about the best-studied virus ever, it amuses me to no end that some believe it might have been cunningly engineered by nefarious boffins to target ethnic group X or Y, or behave in the way it does.(13/13)

Most 'hight-tech' vaccines tend to focus on eliciting narrow antibody responses. T-cell response works best against the whole viral diversity. This raises the question whether there should not be more efforts towards 'traditional' vaccines (i.e. attenuated/inactivated).(12/13)

While there is still no established case of #SARSCoV2 reinfection to date, it is likely those will be observed soon due to fairly fast waning antibodies. Though, anyone with a prior exposure to #SARSCoV2 is expected to experience far less severe symptoms upon reinfection.(11/13)
In contrast to antibody-mediated immunity, T-cell response is extremely long-lived. For example, people infected in 2003 with SARS-1 still mount an immune response to #SARSCoV2 17 years later.(10/13)

There are four known coronaviruses (229E, NL63, OC43, and HKU1) that cause 15-30% of "common colds". They circulate primarily in young children. Most people get infected with one or more of these viruses at some point in their lives.(9/13)

Though, T-cell immunity is essential for controlling an infection and reducing symptoms. #SARSCoV2 seems to elicit robust T-cell response even in asymptomatic/mild patients. There is also evidence for widespread cross-immunity with 'common cold' coronaviruses.(8/13)

T-cell response is a late immune response and does not generally make the host refractory to infection. As such, a vaccine blocking infection would need to elicit a strong antibody-mediated response.(7/13)

T-cell-mediated immunity against #SARSCoV2 has received little attention until recently. The main reasons are that T-cell response is less straightforward to measure and it is generally considered less important for vaccine efficacy.(6/13)

Antibody levels to #SARSCoV2 also wane fairly fast, in line with other coronaviruses. As such, antibody tests can fail to detect prior infection in particular for asymptomatic or mild infections. Serological surveys may underestimate the proportion of people infected.(5/13)

Antibodies are fairly easy to quantify which is the basis of serological tests that inform whether someone has been infected with #SARSCoV2. Though, it is becoming apparent that not everyone infected mounts detectable levels of antibodies.(4/13)

Antibody-mediated (humeral) immunity is based on B‚Äêlymphocytes that are reactivated to produce antibodies when exposed to a pathogen upon reinfection. Until recently, all the attention in the #SARSCoV2 debate has been on antibodies.(3/13)

The immune system is highly complex and comprises a series of different arms. Innate immunity represents mostly first-line responses with no memory of prior infections. Acquired immunity can be broken down into 'antibody-mediated' and 'T-cell-mediated' immunity.(2/13)

Over the last weeks, a substantial amount of new evidence has become available about immunity to #SARSCoV2. This information can be difficult to process and integrate. As such I felt it may be helpful to write a thread to summarise the information and provide some context.(1/13)

I suspect the people pushing for herd immunity without vaccinations haven't thought this through.The person I was interacting with claimed to be a professor of vascular biology. They claimed that herd immunity just happened on its own. This doesn't hapoen with endemic diseases.

The endemic phase only ends if a large enough percentage of everyone develops immunity at the same time.This means broadly available vaccinations or intentional infection by the virus at the same level as vaccination in the 1st strategy. The 2nd strategy means millions dead.

There will always be pockets of population that the virus missed on the last go around. This leads to repeated small outbreaks that keep the virus alive and spreading for long enough that new susceptible people become available.This is the endemic phase of a disease, like now.
The key aspect with both approaches is to induce immunity widely across a population all at once."Natural" herd immunity is a local phenomenon, just like outbreaks are.

Smallpox didn't just disappear on its own.Rinderpest didn't just disappear on its own.Polio isn't now just disappearing on its own.Herd immunity as a strategy either needs immunization or actively infecting & killing the susceptible faster than the virus infects naturally.

It's not always the fault of social media - if brands stopped using social media to find customers, maybe they might start looking elsewhere for monetization. But global, targeted reach is one heck of a drug and I don't think the advertisers are going anywhere.

To expand the circle of problems it solves, big tech needs to collect a ton of data. Brands can't get this data so they rely on social media platforms. Consumers have no better alternative to share things with each other.

I think a lot of distrust in big tech is due to the difficulty in understanding it for what it is: a group of cos that seek to be involved into _every_ aspect of our lives by providing solutions to a set of problems - indirectly through ads or directly through products.

In short, the study does not seem to have been carefully and competently performed. It lacks the required minimal controls, validation and confirmation steps. This is most likely a case of sample mix-up or contamination. (5/6)

There is some uncertainty when the virus arrived in Europe. The first confirmed #COVID19 cases in Europe date back to December 2019. Coronavirus RNA was also detected in wastewater from December 2019 in Milan and Turin, but not before. (2/6)https://t.co/HG6ytRy8hg

It's bittersweet to move on, but I'm thinking of all the people I've worked with tonight with so much gratitude, respect, and affection, which I'll take with me to my new job (end)

I'm continuing as an academic largely because I want to replicate the key ingredients of the environment that has nurtured me these last few years. That's intimidating because I think so much of the people who trained me, but it's also energizing.

Another key to imitate: both of my mentors are serious students of the mentorship process. They make mistakes like everybody else, but they reflect on the process deeply and think of it as a trainable skill. They are also students of their students, learning how each one differs

I can't fully control the impact of the research I do in the future. But there are a few things my mentors did that I *can* emulate: I can always treat the research process with integrity, and I can always treat my labmates and colleagues with respect, kindness, and generosity.

In this moment at the edge of starting my own group, I'm feeling proud and grateful to have been a member of the groups that trained me. I also feel scared that I won't be able to live up to the standards my mentors have set as scientists.

You don't need to wait around for new methods and technologies to solve all your problems - you can just get started with what you can do and if it's a good enough project and you're lucky then the rest of the world will come along with you.

Although I was just a teenager loading gels in a makeshift lab, my involvement in the Human Genome Project has always been something that's shaped my scientific career. It's inspiring to know that ludicrous projects that go at a snail's pace to begin with can accelerate so fast.
I think I even got that grade back the same week that Clinton announced the project had been a success. 20 years ago today. So I was confident that I at least wrote about some worthy automation.

I wrote my final year essay on 'automation in genome sequencing' based on the visit. It was amazing to research how things had changed and dive into the automation and technology. My advisor Ed Southern (of blotting fame) hated it and gave me a 2:2 grade. I still don't know why.

At the start of 2000, I paid a visit back to the Sanger Institute to see how it had changed. It was now a huge place with DNA code flying past on LED screens. It was unrecognisable - rooms and rooms of robots and new sequencers. The same sequencing methods, but industrialised.

It was just simply a case of taking proven methods, optimising them, automating and scaling like crazy. The world had never seen something like this in biology before, and nothing has come close since. It's pretty amazing to look back on.

Sanger sequencing and ABIs still were the workhorses, but switching from slab to capillary sequencing helped the automation, read length and quality. The shotgun method of sequencing certainly made the workflow a lot easier, but couldn't be relied on for gap-less assemblies.

But only 5 years later and it was done! I'd only just had time to finish my biochem degree (it was my final week) and somehow 3.2 billion bp had been read. What's craziest of all is that they didn't really change much since I loaded my gels - they just scaled and automated.

I remember thinking how ludicrous this project was. More than 3 billion bases and we were pipetting every 500 bp read by hand into these annoying gels! It was cool to be involved but it felt it would take a decade more at least.

Most importantly, the patient population gains access to cutting-edge care delivered locally.All in, there's still a lot to figure out, but this is one mechanism we see for rapidly improving guideline compliance and democratizing access to precision oncology.

Because the hospital retains custody of the sample/biomarkers, they can still engage in pharma partnerships. The hospital gains reimbursement, trial therapies, and therapy optimization. The pharma partner builds stronger evidence and gains a companion diagnostic.

A decentralized testing model works differently (see below). Here, a standalone reagent kit is sent to a hospital. The hospital biopsies a patient and runs the diagnostic on premises (or in a core lab). The analytics engine is supplied by the diagnostic company. https://t.co/8PYp0OOoLe

In fact, some pharma companies will reimburse $10K/patient for hospitals to curate clinical data and deliver their therapies. If a hospital sends tissue/blood to a central provider, they lose the ability to bolster pharma partnerships (not good). https://t.co/P5idyFD7JU

Even space-age central diagnostic vendors don't focus on the community setting because of low sales ROI. But wait, there's more:Regulators, patient networks, and biopharma are pushing hard to run trials in remote hospitals. It makes for stronger, more representative data.

Precision therapies only work if we give them to people (who would have thought?). This bifurcation in care quality also is a source of health disparity.This gap occurs for several reasons: physician awareness, rural testing infrastructure, and ...

Is there really a need to fly to MD Anderson or MSK for modern cancer care?85% of American cancer patients are treated in smaller, community hospitals. Only a minority of these patients receive guideline-recommended biomarker testing and only 3% have access to clinal trials. https://t.co/x9U5ForfXr

Can cutting-edge precision oncology be delivered to small, regional hospital systems? [Thread Warning üö®]TL;DR: Yes, though it may need to be carried out through a decentralized diagnostic model built on synthetic biology, edge computing, and biopharma partnerships.

11/n Finally, we find that the implicit regularizer induced by the model parametrization has a large impact on the spectra of adversarial attacks. In sum, we believe that using dynamics can give us interesting insights into the development and nature of adversarial examples.

10/n showing that it is the interaction between the parametrization and the dataset that leads to these low amplitude high-frequency attacks. This result also holds for nonlinear models, where the increase in expressive power amplifies these differences. https://t.co/5kePsyBl1k

9/n Furthermore, we found that the convolutional operation (Bounded-Width Convolution),via translation invariance, produces models with higher frequency adversarial perturbations, as compared to the other models. This is the case even when all the models have the same performance https://t.co/KU10k51IPi
8/n We found that this relationship between the implicit regularizer of the model and the adversarial perturbations holds for several different models. https://t.co/7nDWE0sf8r

7/n We confirmed this theory, via training fully connected and full-width convolutional models on CIFAR-10, where we observed that the latter have sparser adversarial perturbation spectra. https://t.co/ugeu0ic9tv

6/n For this we used theory develop by Gunasekar et al 2019, where they found that full width convolutional linear models induce an L1 implicit regularizer in the Fourier spectrum of the end-to-end linear predictor,  compared to an L2 regularizer in fully connected linear models.

5/n Then, we asked: is the high-frequency structure in adversarial examples only due to the dataset? Or is it also dependent on the model parametrization via the Implicit Regularization? We explored this first in linear models.

4/n In addition, we found that in a ResNet Model trained on CIFAR-10, there is a dynamical evolution from low to high frequencies in the adversarial perturbations.  The small figures show the average 2D Fourier spectrum of the adversarial perturbations as a function of training. https://t.co/fXvm2rZ2iP

3/n First, using a continuous piecewise linear analysis, we found that breakpoints move to adversarial directions during training, indicating that adversarial directions are caused by useful features in the data, not just overparametrization or over/underfitting of the model. https://t.co/R4k46nUzvi

2/n Inspired by the work from @aleks_madry,  we decided to explore if/how the nature of adversarial perturbations depends on the interaction btw the dataset and the implicit regularization imposed by the model parametrization via the dynamic evolution of adversarial examples.

1/n Excited to share my latest work with @yilongj,@Ryanpyle_1,@abp4_ankit on the relationship btw Implicit Regularization and Adversarial Examples, titled "Using Learning Dynamics to Explore the Role of Implicit Regularization in Adversarial Examples" https://t.co/peN847dQlo

They coated mouse DCs with these two 8mer peptides and injected them IV into 8-to-9 month old B6 mice. They then boosted this immunization at 6 days with intranasal rVV (recombinant vaccinia) with minigenes encoding the same peptides. Viral challenge ~6 weeks later. https://t.co/2zZWIrPDwg

They developed a murine adapted SARS virus (rMA15), removed its envelope protein (rMA15-ŒîE) and showed that it infects mice (and leads to SARS-like disease). This strain has at least two immunodominant cytotoxic T-cell epitopes in B6 mice: S436-443 & S525-532.

The authors review the three challenges faced when assaying TE expression -- 1) their mappability, 2) their variability and 3) the diversity of their transcripts -- and detail the computational and experimental approaches that can help solve these issues https://t.co/k9GCGOqxQT
Moreover, many TE-containing transcripts are not implicated in TE mobilization but rather are gene-TE chimeric transcripts or result from pervasive transcription https://t.co/la7UoZztwl

Measuring TE expression is not straightforward; not only are TEs highly repeated in their host genome but insertional polymorphisms (presence/absence) and internal sequence polymorphisms between individuals complicate their identification https://t.co/NAINzLH1WY

Computational tools to analyse RNA-seq data often discard reads derived from transposable elements (TE) but measuring TE expression helps to understand when and where TE mobilization occurs and how it alters gene expression, chromatin accessibility or cellular signalling pathways https://t.co/3esq0U5oAq

Influenza mortality varies greatly depending on lineage and population immunity. #COVID19 is currently in its 'pandemic' phase. Its IFR is higher than those of the 1968/69 and 2009 influenza pandemic lineages, similar to the 1957/59 one and below the 1918/19 strain.(6/6)

Flu pandemics are caused by new influenza lineages and lead to dramatic excess mortality. Though, some endemic flu seasons can occasionally be locally severe. The 1951 'endemic' flu season in the UK/Canada caused excess deaths on the 1918/19 scale.(5/6)https://t.co/1X1l8PPChJ https://t.co/o47fYmZcRN

The three lineages of Influenza A in circulation today are descendants of those that caused the 1918/19 H1N1, 1968/69 H3N2 and 2009 H1N1 influenza pandemics. All three have since become endemic as the population acquired immunity to them.(4/6) https://t.co/bJxZ79yvlG

Influenza A is more severe than influenza B, and causes the majority of the 3-5 million yearly cases of severe illness with ~500,000 deaths in 'good years'. Though, influenza A itself comprises three lineages currently in circulation that vary in symptom severity.(3/6)

There are three major Influenza types infecting humans, A, B and C. Influenza A and B cause seasonal flu, with one winter and one spring epidemic each year, the winter epidemic is generally far more deadly.(2/6) https://t.co/i82ckMDVPV

Comparing #COVID19 infection fatality rates (IFRs) of #SARSCoV2 with influenza can be problematic. As the piece below touches on, the IFR estimates for seasonal influenza are very poor. Though, another more important reason is that 'influenza' conflates many things.(1/6) https://t.co/wDJKaGXtiA

As we mention in the discussion, bimmer is a tool for causal network discovery/hypothesis generation: formal causal claims require deep domain expertise. That said, we highlight some interesting examples in the paper. We'd welcome (constructive!) feedback.

Application to 405 @uk_biobank traits gives a network with 2826 edges and remarkable properties: highly variable out-degree (0 for 75% but >100 for 5), high connectivity (every node is reachable from any non-zero out-degree node) and pervasive mediation (median path length of 2).
@BrielinB did a fantastic job pushing through tricky technical obstacles to come up with a method that, in simulations, knocks the socks off anything else we could think of for this problem.

The idea is to find a parsimonious network that explains pairwise MR-estimated total causal effects using direct and mediated effects, like how the graphical lasso finds a sparse precision matrix that explains the empirical covariance (but with directed edges!) Cycles allowed!

Excited to share the lab's first genetics preprint from the awesome @BrielinB: bimmer, an approach for inferring causal networks over many traits using Mendelian randomization (MR). https://t.co/YKs5YhOxxU and code is at https://t.co/40kUWl2aga.

they still use the total causal effect matrix for looking at the overall causal structure as a whole (defining subgraphs, etc). This is very analogous to correlations/partial correlations - correlation matrices are generally a lot more useful for defining subgraphs of interest 8/ https://t.co/ubW5unKQaI

They applied the method to estimate direct causal effects  between traits of the UK biobank. An interesting thing that I found in downstream analysis of the trait networks is that they use direct causal effects to examine individual pairs or paths between traits, but... 7/

What I found clever here though, is that at the same time they also shrink the total causal effect matrix, in a way correcting the possibly noisy total effect matrix and calculating its inverse in one shot. The inverse is then used to calculate the direct causal effects 6/

Precision matrices for partial correlations are tough to calculate, and one typically uses regularized (by sparsity) or "shrunk" approximations. In the same way, the authors calculate a shrunken version of the inverse total causal effects. 5/

Pairwise total causal effects like the ones computed with Mendelian randomization have the same problem of lumping indirect effects. So can we get an analogous "partial correlation" for causal effects? Turns out yes, but you need the inverse of the total causal effect matrix 4/ https://t.co/DIP7d5ub4F

To disentangle these, one typically uses partial correlations, which correct for the indirect effects. Interestingly, just like the matrix of pairwise correlations is a normalized covariance matrix, partial correlations is a normalized inverse covariance (or precision) matrix. 3/

Pairwise correlations are useful to get a sense of the structure of dependencies between variables.But correlations between pairs (A,B) contain not only the direct dependency between A and B, but also all the indirect dependencies of other variables from A to B lumped together 2/

<< puts populations like Sardinians, Orkney Islanders and the general 15% of people who self identify as "White British" in the UK BioBank ethnicity survey but don't make it to the main "blob" into a tricky situation.

This is obviously really complex for big structures in our society - eg, in the UK, Black British (in all their complexity - Black British in Liverpool, Afro-Caribbean, recent Black African which itself should be split into fine details) but also >>

So - now there is a big distinction here between discovery - where we have these ways by sub-selecting populations and throwing in PCs from prediction and modelling and using - where we just don't have the tools to estimate things.

This is even though the first 20 genetic PCs *are* a good model for the environmental effects that "happen" to be non random wrt to genetic effects (eg, allele drift, for UK BioBank, mainly North-South).

However this is a *big deal* when we want to think about total population. Just to be straightforward - the 1st 20 genetic prinicpals component of the UK BioBank is unlikely to capture well the social environment structure of all of the UK

This is a complex way of saying our societies have plenty of discrimination and other components that track with complex genetic structure - eg, straightforwardly, discrimination. We don't worry too much about this; we don't think too hard about this for genetic discovery.

But I want to loop back to the first bit, where the standard human genetics protocol is to select a subset of the population. This has to have certain genetic properties, but it is also likely to have certain social environment properties.

Lots of experience now says that done well it *is* valid (though many of us will endlessly point out that the fact this "PC covariate" trick works in this discovery setting doesn't mean it is going to work everywhere else) and for (b) the number of results are enough anyway

Back in the mid-2000s there was much angst if this whole selecting a subset of the population plus kitchen sink of PCs would work. (a) is it valid? and (b) are we losing power to find some trans/background effects.

Those multiple sublethal alterations on A. cerana's behavior indicate that TMX is likely to have complex but negative consequences on bee health in the field.
Our study also highlights the concern that acute oral exposure to a low concentration of 2.4 ppb could have consequences on the behavior of A. creana.
Results suggest that acute oral exposure to 10 ppb of TMX altered the short-distance homing time, flight ability, and learning acquisition and short-term retention ability.
Bees treated with either 2.4 ppb or 10 ppb TMX had significantly lower learning acquisition and short-term retention ability.

Results When treated with 10 ppb of TMX, bees had a significantly higher average homing time, mean flight velocity, flying distance, and flying duration than the control, whereas 2.4 ppb concentration did not cause any significant effect on homing or flight ability.

The homing ability was assessed by the catch-and-release method, the flight ability was assessed by flight mills, and the learning acquisition and short-term retention were evaluated by the proboscis extension response (PER) method.

We carried out three independent experiments to study the impact of acute oral treatment of 20 mu L TMX at concentrations of 2.4 ppb (0.048 ng/bee) and 10 ppb (0.2 ng/bee) on the homing, flight, learning acquisition and short-term retention ability of A. cerana.

Thiamethoxam (TMX) represents the second generation of neonicotinoids that have been widely applied in agricultural activities, while how TMX alters the behavior of Apis cerana, an important native honey bee species in China, is not clear.

LAMP gives multiple copies of the target into a long read, and it can have a 10nt bar code. Easy dual bar code, but also the first "LAMP" barcode is *in the LAMP tube*. By having a beta-actin internal control to distinguish "negatives" from "failed reaction" / "failed swab"

LAMP traditionally coupled to a colour change (of flourescent primers nearby) but these have false positives (weird dimers) and dodgy "mid colour" changes. Rather than using fluorophore, ligate nanopore primers, and then put on a nanopore

The rifampicin drug-resistance mutation rpoB450 was associated to reduced lung damage, suggestive of a fitness cost to the bacterium in vivo. Conversely, the rpoC1040 mutation known to compensate for the fitness cost of rpoB450 was associated with more severe lung damage.3/4 https://t.co/jTIm7goN2M

The 10umol/L threshold is corroborated by an analysis of ECG QRS durations. QRS prolongation is a well known marker of chloroquine toxicity.QRS durations above 150 msec are really only seen at concentrations above 10umol/L. QRS is an independent predictor of death. 5/n https://t.co/NvRslLQOlZ

This is why having diverse images from the VERY beginning of medical education matters.  #FOAMed #medtwitter #dermtwitter Also: shout out to @DermDocJenna, whose mentorship and scholarship is constantly inspiring me, including inspiring this thought experiment.

If we started from a place of diversity at the very beginning, we would not have trained our mental models to rely so much on the features particular to white skin.  We would have picked up other cues or created more holistic mental models for assessing skin lesions.

We (I am guilty of this too) talk about how difficult it is to diagnose a disease in skin of color because we can't assess the "redness". But that issue is only because our education made white skin the default. And we didn't get enough diversity in our teaching images.

Our study helps quantify the impact of DTCGT on clinical genetics services, and highlights the impact of imputed risk estimates. @JaneMTiller @AusGenomics

> 30% of referrals involved imputed risk estimates from third-party software tools. Services reported low validation rates for DTCGT results (<10%), and variable procedures for managing DTCGT referrals, with most (8/11) lacking specific procedures.4/n

We surveyed Australian clinical genetics services about DTCGT-related referrals over the past 10 years. Eleven publicly-funded services reported over 100 DTCGT-related referrals. Most (83%) involved general practitioners seeking interpretation of DTCGT results. 3/n

The increasing popularity of direct-to-consumer genetic testing (DTCGT) is thought to be creating a burden on clinical genetic services worldwide. However, no Australian studies have collected recent evidence regarding this impact. 2/n

Do you ever think for a minute how far technology has gone? 20 years ago, we had to spend 3 billion dollars to get *one* human genome sequenced. Now, we have access to the transcriptome of *single* cells, or the complete genome of *thousands* of individuals

Finally, a plea again for solidarity - this a "humans vs the virus" situation - it is not about countries, less so even groups inside a country. Very simply we want to eliminate the virus or live comfortably alongside it. We should stay focused on that goal.
The diversity of companies and diversity of approaches means we have many "shots on goal". Again, no guarentee one will work, but we have got to be happy at the rate of progress of the vaccines.

4. Finally there are a large number of vaccines in the pipeline with earliest in Phase III trials now (I am actually in the trial, going for my randomised dose of Oxford vaccine or Meningitis tomorrow).

Large, well powered, adaptive trials are the way forward here. Negative results is depressing but they remove the endless opportunity cost of wondering what could work and focus us on the cases that might.

3. We have well powered clinical trials coming in; I am a particular fan of the UK's RECOVERY trial. It is nailed down for example that one drug (HCQ) does not change the course of the disease. Other drugs are progressing through the trials.
We should be in a position to watch the virus far more closely than before and identify any incipient outbreaks/clusters (a key part of the Japanese strategy as well).

The near future is positive for testing respiratory virus panels (going to be v. useful in autumn/winter when other colds and flu come back) and testing pooled resources for surveillance - Sewage in particular could be really useful.

No matter what the technology used, testing capacity is going to go up - we will need to focus on other areas of bottlenecking here - people/swab/spit logistics. Again, operationalising this is complex, but doable.

2. Testing levels are higher + I hope will go higher still. I have a whopping conflict of interest here, as one of the next-scale testing technologies is @nanopore's LamPORE which is undergoing final trials before regulatory submission. I am a long established consultant to ONT
(It is one thing to see this aggregate response, and another thing to learn, operationalise and implement them in another location, but it is doable. Humans can live alongside this virus).

1. A number of countries have reasonably light rules with still active infections - South Korea and Japan stand out for me. This suggests a subset of non-pharmaceutical interventions - rules of behaviour - can dramatically reduce transmission rates.

(4) Prioritization still happens during Cycle Planning, but on shaped projects, not raw ideas. "What gets shaped" could be chosen based on intuition. Formal prioritization is still done with team.

In any cycle,(2) engineers build 80% of the time and shapes 20% of the time. Whole team should NOT be pulled into every shaping conversation. (3) PO and architect shape for next cycle 80% and assist in building for current cycle 20%.
To summarize this thread, what I want to experiment with to solve this dilemma are (1) Parallel tracks of building and shaping during a cycle.

Thus far, what we've done is (1) We prioritize unshaped raw ideas together, (2) We shape during building. This makes everything slow. And engineers don't like it anyway. Every step reveals an open question and slows them down.

My key struggle as a PO has always been: (1) I want team to prioritize together (2) I want team to be involved in deciding what we can build to solve the problem. But (3) how to do these without taking away too much eng'g focus time from building?
We‚Äôre not making decisions, just shaping some projects. At the end of the day, prioritization is still done by the team in the betting table.

‚ÄúWhat gets shaped" could be chosen based on intuition by me or whoever else wants to make a pitch, really. We won‚Äôt invest a lot of time shaping. Just a few hours or days, at most. And won‚Äôt involve the whole team.
‚ÄúThis isn‚Äôt a spec. It‚Äôs more like the boundaries and rules of a game.‚Äù

The difference is, instead of prioritizing raw ideas, we will be prioritizing shaped projects. The key is project pitches should be made specific and concrete, while leaving lots of space for technical decisions and choices to be made by the engineers.
In Giant Swarm, again, this will be done by the team who builds. We do this in Halo and Batman already in our Cycle Planning.
Betting -- In Basecamp, this Betting / Prioritization is done by the CEO, CTO, a senior programmer, and a product person. They decide what to do in the next cycle.

Maybe @illumina and @PacBio were already eyeing each other in 2013-2014 (I doubt it), but a few years ago, a big VP at @illumina left and joined @PacBio , and we now know of the failed merger between the two (quiet possibly for the right reasons).

In 2013-2014, Jay Flatley, the then CEO at @Illumina came to the UK offices when I was working there, and I, being the new guy and not having much to lose, asked him in front of 400 people: "when are we going to buy @PacBio ?". He replied nicely and non-committedly.

... the technology has advanced by several-fold since then. Mike Hunkapiller led the improvements at @PacBio at a time when @illumina was (and is) the dominant player, and many were wondering if there ever was going to be a competing technology for #NGS .

Each of the above decisions is rational. But, we value diversity so we look for additional resources for the URM candidate and when we don‚Äôt get it we blame the admins. But, hey we really value diversity and the stingy admins are not supportive. We are frustrated!4/n

Finally, I want to apologise. I made the error in the OOA model, and I should have checked it more carefully. Msprime users have been affected, and I'm truly sorry for this. Documentation examples will be tested with the same rigor as library code in the future.

Thanks to my coathors @SFGravel, Dom Nelson and @apragsdale for getting this together so quickly. Particularly and especially to Aaron, for finding the OOA bug in the first place and then analysing it so thoroughly.

There are two major lessons for me: (1) we *really* need stdpopsim. Defining these simulation models is hard, and they should not be reimplemented over and over. (2) we need better tools. Msprime's demography API is not easy enough to use, and we're working to fix that.

The OOA model has now been fixed in stdpopsim (version 0.1.2) and msprime's documentation. We have tried to identify copies of the faulty model and contacted the owners to alert them.  See here for more details: https://t.co/X6AmES3PP0

We only found the error in the Out-of-Africa model because of the quality-control process for stdpopsim. This is a community-maintained "standard library" of species data and population genetic models from the PopSim consortium. https://t.co/STatsA5U37

In the preprint we also discuss a related error in some simulations for @genetisaur et al's 2017 AJHG paper. A simple, easy-to-make error has a significant effect on the simulations (but not overall conclusions). See their preprint for details: https://t.co/GXIUKFHAqz

Important announcement for #msprime users. For 4 years the Out-of-Africa population model example in msprime's documentation  was *incorrect*. This example has been copied and built on many times, so the error has propagated. See our preprint for details: https://t.co/0mPEhphNf2

HS has gained more research interest in recent years, but there's still a lot that's unknown.But we do know that HS is NOT caused by poor hygeine, and it's NOT contagious.

It causes painful boils and lesions, and ranges in severity from a few bumps here and there to large tracts of affected tissue that may require surgical intervention.There's no cure, but there are treatments with varying levels of success depending on the individual.

Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS), also known as acne inversa and a few other names, is a chronic autoinflammatory condition that affects apocrine (sweat) glands. It primarily affects women, though anyone can get it.HS was once thought to be rare, but it's pretty common.

8/8: Most of checkpoint inhibition is focused on reinvigorating CD8s. Pretty excited about cytotoxic CD4s as another axis of antitumor immunity and exploring how the incredible phenotypic diversity/plasticity of CD4s can be leveraged for therapy.

7/8: Cyto CD4s have historically been dismissed as artifacts of cell culture. Recently, there has been renewed interest in their role in antiviral response. They have also been described in other cancers and bear some resemblance to peripheral helper T cells in autoimmunity.
6/8: A gene expression signature specific to cyto CD4s is associated with response to checkpoint blockade in an independent bulk RNA-seq dataset.

5/8: To validate their function, we co-cultured cyto CD4s with autologous bladder tumor cells in vitro, and showed they can kill tumor in a MHC II dependent way that appears to be partially inhibited by Tregs. Cyto CD4s kill slower than CD8s but not by much. https://t.co/jKJEfthOI1

4/8: Cyto CD4s are also clonally expanded based on TCR sequencing (to do this...we had to build a custom amplification strategy off of the @10xGenomics 3' V1 full-length libraries and got ~50% recovery of paired TCRA/TCRB sequences.) https://t.co/CrA5fVxCHX

3/8: What was surprising is we also found multiple cytotoxic CD4 populations. Cyto CD4s are distinguished by the expression of GZMK and GZMB and they are very similar transcriptionally to analogous CD8 T cell populations. https://t.co/dgcsPp8aiM

2/8: We used single cell RNA/TCR-sequencing to characterize ~30k tumor infiltrating CD4 and CD8 T cells. CD4s are more abundant and primarily consist of two populations of regulatory T cells (IL25hi and IL25lo). These Tregs are clonally expanded and do not appear to be induced. https://t.co/Kr20d1WSbD
